This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with dialogue act classification in group chats. It also involves the use of machine learning models such as hierarchical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and long short-term memory (LSTM) networks, which are commonly used in natural language processing tasks. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the use of deep neural network models for classification. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category as the paper discusses the use of traditional machine learning models as well as deep neural network models. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is a possible sub-category as the paper deals with multi-party conversations and the turn-taking structure present in them. 

Finally, cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is a possible sub-category as the paper discusses the use of machine learning models for conversation analytics, which could be relevant to information retrieval tasks.
